  "response": "Research suggests there is a correlation between narcissistic personality traits and substance abuse, though the exact percentage varies across studies:\n\n1. Comorbidity:\n- Studies indicate higher rates of substance abuse among individuals with Narcissistic Personality Disorder (NPD)\n- Estimates range from 40-50% having co-occurring substance use disorders\n\n2. Underlying factors:\n- Narcissists may use drugs to:\n  - Enhance self-image\n  - Cope with perceived failures\n  - Seek attention or validation\n  - Manage underlying emotional insecurities\n\n3. Psychological mechanisms:\n- Impulsivity\n- Poor emotional regulation\n- Risk-taking behaviors\n- Grandiose self-perception\n- Difficulty accepting personal limitations\n\n4. Important nuances:\n- Not all narcissists are drug users\n- Not all substance abusers are narcissists\n- Individual variations are significant\n- Professional diagnosis requires comprehensive assessment\n\n5. Research limitations:\n- Limited large-scale studies\n- Diagnostic complexity\n- Potential reporting biases\n\nWhile a significant correlation exists, it's crucial to avoid overgeneralization and recognize individual differences in personality and substance use patterns.\n\nProfessional psychological evaluation is recommended for accurate assessment.",
